WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

00:00:09.000 --> 00:00:16.000
I'm just going to record a little brief announcement just for the table, so we have a record of that and then we'll just start talking.

00:00:16.000 --> 00:00:18.000
Are you ready?

00:00:18.000 --> 00:00:19.000
Ready.

00:00:19.000 --> 00:00:20.000
Fantastic.

00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:21.000
You're on.

00:00:21.000 --> 00:00:22.000
Okay.

00:00:22.000 --> 00:00:33.000
Today is October the 3rd, 2013. We're in Shreveport, Louisiana, and the beautiful sanctuary of the Mount Canaan Baptist Church with Reverend Dr. Harry Blake.

00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:34.000
Good morning.

00:00:34.000 --> 00:00:35.000
Good morning. Good to have you here.

00:00:35.000 --> 00:00:36.000
Thank you so much.

00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:37.000
Welcome to the hood.

00:00:37.000 --> 00:00:38.000
Thank you. Thank you.

00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:48.000
This is David Cline talking of the Virginia Louisiana Tech History Department and also working with the Southern Oral History Program at UNC Chapel Hill.

00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:59.000
And we are here on behalf of the Civil Rights History Project of the National Museum of African American History and Culture of the Smithsonian and the Library of Congress.

00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:04.000
Behind the camera today is John Bishop of Media Generation and UCLA.

00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:12.000
So again, thank you so much for being part of this project. We really appreciate your time and your willingness to be part of this.

00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:15.000
It's really, it's extremely gratifying to have you here.

00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:18.000
Thank you so much.

00:01:18.000 --> 00:01:29.000
Where I'd like to start, if you would, is if you could just tell us a bit about your upbringing and where your people and where you came from.

00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:37.000
And we'll try and tie that into a conversation about the work you've done on behalf of African American people in the Civil Rights Movement.

00:01:37.000 --> 00:01:38.000
Good.

00:01:38.000 --> 00:01:46.000
Oh, my parents, my daddy was born in Mississippi. My mother was born in Arkansas.

00:01:46.000 --> 00:01:54.000
And I was born in Arkansas, but being the land of opportunity, the first opportunity my parents got.

00:01:54.000 --> 00:01:58.000
They seized it and got me out of Arkansas and brought me to Louisiana.

00:01:58.000 --> 00:02:00.000
Very, very young.

00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:08.000
My background is that of a plantation. My daddy was a sharecropper who could not read a write.

00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:11.000
I think my mother finished third grade.

00:02:11.000 --> 00:02:17.000
So I was reared and lived on a plantation having been born in 1934.

00:02:17.000 --> 00:02:27.000
I lived on a plantation till I was 24 years old, finished college. That was the year I finished college that I like to say I was liberated from the plantation.

00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:31.000
My wife liberated me from the plantation.

00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:39.000
Went to a one-room church school.

00:02:39.000 --> 00:02:43.000
It was a public school. I guess you can describe it this way.

00:02:43.000 --> 00:02:53.000
The plantation owner established your school in a church building for first through seventh grades.

00:02:53.000 --> 00:03:02.000
And that teacher was not really a college graduate. She was a college sophomore.

00:03:02.000 --> 00:03:07.000
She taught first through seventh grade, every subject.

00:03:07.000 --> 00:03:10.000
So obviously it was not a lot she could do.

00:03:10.000 --> 00:03:17.000
So I was almost a teenager before I learned to read and write.

00:03:18.000 --> 00:03:23.000
I was promoted to junior high. I guess you would say eighth grade.

00:03:23.000 --> 00:03:31.000
And that was my first encounter with the eight parts of speech and other things.

00:03:31.000 --> 00:03:34.000
Because I was behind.

00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:36.000
But I struggled to catch up.

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:40.000
And as a matter of fact, my whole life has been a life of trying to catch up.

00:03:40.000 --> 00:03:47.000
And by the time I've caught up in this century, here comes technology.

00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:50.000
And technology changes every week.

00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:53.000
We all feel that.

00:03:53.000 --> 00:03:57.000
This may not be meaningful.

00:03:57.000 --> 00:04:03.000
I plowed mules. Here I am. Here I am in high school plowing mules.

00:04:03.000 --> 00:04:12.000
And I decided for some unknown reason that I was not going to learn the language of the mule.

00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:15.000
I was going to teach the mule my language.

00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:19.000
And mule language was Whoa, gee, haw".

00:04:19.000 --> 00:04:26.000
And I discovered that it was not in what you said to the mule that got his attention.

00:04:26.000 --> 00:04:29.000
It was the pull of the reins.

00:04:29.000 --> 00:04:32.000
So when I wanted the mule to stop, I just said stop.

00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:34.000
And I pulled on the rains.

00:04:34.000 --> 00:04:38.000
If I wanted to go right, I said to the right.

00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:40.000
And I pulled on the right range.

00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:43.000
So that's a humorous story, but it's true.

00:04:43.000 --> 00:04:45.000
I did not learn mule language.

00:04:45.000 --> 00:04:47.000
I had intelligent mules.

00:04:47.000 --> 00:04:50.000
I taught them my language.

00:04:50.000 --> 00:04:52.000
That's the humor of it.

00:04:52.000 --> 00:04:55.000
Well, what lesson did you learn there with the mules?

00:04:55.000 --> 00:04:58.000
How did you apply that later in life, if any way?

00:04:59.000 --> 00:05:00.000
Let me add this.

00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:08.000
My daddy taught me that there was a saying that you can lead a horse through the water, but you can't make him drink.

00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:19.000
My daddy said, if you know how and put enough salt in his diet, he'll find water on his own.

00:05:19.000 --> 00:05:26.000
I learned a powerful lesson from that in my pastoral ministry.

00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:40.000
If I have a project, have a mission that the church does not see eye to eye, I sought the diet to make them first for what I'm trying to feed them.

00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:43.000
So that has been very beneficial to me.

00:05:43.000 --> 00:05:55.000
I learned also from this mule thing, if you know how, you can get people to do anything you want them to do.

00:05:55.000 --> 00:06:00.000
I saw examples of that from Jim Jones and David Koresh.

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:11.000
They took lettered people, unlettered people, rich people, poor people, and met them to do whatever they wanted them to do.

00:06:11.000 --> 00:06:23.000
Mr. Jim Jones even said to people, stand in line and drink poison, and they were anxious to do that.

00:06:23.000 --> 00:06:33.000
So I think as a clergy person, you got to keep your motives right so you can lead people in the right direction.

00:06:33.000 --> 00:06:41.000
Those were some leadership skills that I learned from the plantation and from life.

00:06:41.000 --> 00:06:44.000
When were you called to the church?

00:06:45.000 --> 00:06:55.000
That's my pastoral year in my pastoral days in the rural community.

00:06:55.000 --> 00:07:00.000
I should just pause and ask you where exactly was the plantation.

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:05.000
I lived on two plantations.

00:07:05.000 --> 00:07:17.000
One was in northeast Louisiana in Madison Parish, Tallulah, Louisiana, and the name of that plantation was the Ashley plantation.

00:07:17.000 --> 00:07:34.000
Left there in 1951 and moved to Northwest Louisiana's Shreveport, Shreveport, and the plantation north of Shreveport was the Wood Spur plantation.

00:07:34.000 --> 00:07:44.000
That's the plantation that I was liberated from. I went to college and after I finished college, moved to the city limits of Shreveport.

00:07:44.000 --> 00:07:53.000
So my first passage was in 1958 in Shreveport, a one-sunday church.

00:07:53.000 --> 00:07:59.000
That was the tradition of the rural areas churches did not meet every Sunday.

00:07:59.000 --> 00:08:07.000
Some churches met every other Sunday, for instance, first and a third Sunday, or second and fourth Sunday.

00:08:07.000 --> 00:08:12.000
So my first church was a one-sunday church, first Sunday.

00:08:12.000 --> 00:08:20.000
And then I was called to a church closer to Shreveport, almost in the city limits.

00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:26.000
It was a first Sunday evening and a third Sunday morning church.

00:08:26.000 --> 00:08:35.000
I got called to that church, and then I got called just on the line of texts. It's called Bethany, Louisiana.

00:08:35.000 --> 00:08:50.000
I got called to a second and fourth Sunday church. By 1967, 1966, I was able to turn those two rural churches full time.

00:08:50.000 --> 00:09:05.000
To satisfy my conscience, I left both of those churches because I didn't want to go to one or the other and came to this church, which was 1966.

00:09:05.000 --> 00:09:15.000
This church was in the most densely populated slum area of Shreveport called Allendale.

00:09:15.000 --> 00:09:33.000
And I came here. Unfortunately, this church was not in a sense as advanced as my rural churches because we had air conditioning in the rural church and pews.

00:09:33.000 --> 00:09:40.000
This church did not have air conditioning at the time. Now pews, we had benches and all that good stuff.

00:09:40.000 --> 00:09:49.000
The building that I inherited was so dilapidated that I think a few years after I was here, it actually collapsed and fell in.

00:09:49.000 --> 00:09:54.000
And this is the result of that building having been so dilapidated.

00:09:54.000 --> 00:10:01.000
So I've been here since 1966, 47 years this year.

00:10:01.000 --> 00:10:04.000
That's wonderful.

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:13.000
So let's talk a little bit about, let me ask you first, growing up on the two plantations.

00:10:13.000 --> 00:10:24.000
What was it like for African American people in that time as far as opportunities available and as far as relationship with white people?

00:10:24.000 --> 00:10:32.000
Let me respond to the last part of that question, relationship to white people.

00:10:32.000 --> 00:10:42.000
This is interesting and a lot of people don't know this or may not agree.

00:10:42.000 --> 00:10:53.000
White and Blacks, any confined narrow sense had great relationships.

00:10:53.000 --> 00:11:07.000
For instance, if you were the white man's boy, you got whatever you need with certain restrictions.

00:11:07.000 --> 00:11:22.000
I remember when the World War II, if you were a good worker on the plantation, you didn't get drafted to the military.

00:11:22.000 --> 00:11:33.000
One reason is that the farmers were on the draft board of whatever it's called.

00:11:33.000 --> 00:11:38.000
And if his Negro's name came up, got set aside.

00:11:38.000 --> 00:11:50.000
I remember this expression. They would say at the end of the week when you got that day off, the go to town, the tea tell you, have a good time.

00:11:50.000 --> 00:11:58.000
If you stay out of the cemetery, mean don't get killed, I'll keep you out of jail.

00:11:58.000 --> 00:12:03.000
That meant you could kill another Negro.

00:12:03.000 --> 00:12:10.000
You could do whatever you want just since you don't get into the white area. I'll get you out of jail.

00:12:10.000 --> 00:12:21.000
That's the kind of relationship. White and Blacks, in a confined sense, got along very well.

00:12:21.000 --> 00:12:41.000
I think, perhaps even today, my younger years would do anything for his Negro so long as he felt like he was handing it down to him, but not out to him.

00:12:41.000 --> 00:12:49.000
Not on my, you will never be my equal. That's the way I describe the relationship.

00:12:49.000 --> 00:12:54.000
And as you say, his Negro, so there's a sense of that.

00:12:54.000 --> 00:13:01.000
You never forget you were mine. And the people who live on plantation were really his Negro.

00:13:01.000 --> 00:13:05.000
And I'm using the language that was popular and they didn't Negro.

00:13:05.000 --> 00:13:15.000
Because if you were a sharecropper, he provided a hut house for you to live in.

00:13:15.000 --> 00:13:31.000
He provided the food for you to eat because he had what they call a commissary, a country store that he provided food and implements for farming and some clothing worklotings.

00:13:31.000 --> 00:13:37.000
You got an advance on that. He would charge that to your account.

00:13:37.000 --> 00:13:48.000
You had to use his muse to work the crop and his implements the plows and cultivators.

00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:51.000
So he charged that to your account.

00:13:51.000 --> 00:13:58.000
Now, let's say you were able to grow 20 bales of cotton.

00:13:58.000 --> 00:14:04.000
10 of those bales belonged to the farm, their owner.

00:14:04.000 --> 00:14:13.000
10 belonged to you and you paid the expenses for making those 20 bales out of your income.

00:14:13.000 --> 00:14:24.000
And most of the time, at the end of the year, he would say to the plantation workers, you did good this year.

00:14:24.000 --> 00:14:32.000
We broke even. Now you can't leave the plantation and go somewhere else.

00:14:32.000 --> 00:14:41.000
You could leave the plantation if another farmer paid him to let you move to his plantation.

00:14:41.000 --> 00:14:48.000
So you are always indebted. You owed your soul to the company store.

00:14:48.000 --> 00:14:58.000
My daddy, fortunately, I don't know how he did it. I guess he must have found favor in the white owner.

00:14:58.000 --> 00:15:08.000
He always, every year, would make a profit, maybe $200, not more than $500 a year.

00:15:08.000 --> 00:15:19.000
And how we got from North East Louisiana to Northwest Louisiana, the manager,

00:15:19.000 --> 00:15:33.000
followed the owner of the plantation, was offered a job in North Louisiana and he was allowed to bring as many of the Negroes from this plantation with him.

00:15:33.000 --> 00:15:43.000
But he paid the owner. So we owed him. And you never got out of debt. You were always in debt.

00:15:43.000 --> 00:15:58.000
And if I can sneak this in, America is pretty much on that style today because they keep us slaves with credit cards.

00:15:58.000 --> 00:16:03.000
You asked me another question that I didn't address. I don't remember what he was.

00:16:03.000 --> 00:16:12.000
Well, I asked about relations with white people. But just what it was like, I guess, within the black community as well at that time, how cohesive black communities were.

00:16:12.000 --> 00:16:17.000
And I also want to ask about, if anyone was voting at that time.

00:16:17.000 --> 00:16:31.000
No, no, no, no. No one was voting. The plantation that I lived on, when I became twenty years old, no black person was registered.

00:16:31.000 --> 00:16:44.000
There might have been a handful of blacks in that part of Shreveport, Dixie, not Dixie.

00:16:44.000 --> 00:16:56.000
Well, yeah, maybe Dixie, Belcher might have been a handful. How I got registered at, I believe the age limit then was twenty-one.

00:16:56.000 --> 00:17:11.000
How I got registered, I gave an address of a friend of mine who lived in the city limits as my address.

00:17:11.000 --> 00:17:21.000
And I studied the past test that was required in this state and in this parish.

00:17:21.000 --> 00:17:31.000
So at twenty-one, though I was still on the plantation, I became a registered voter.

00:17:31.000 --> 00:17:35.000
Now, do you remember what that process was, what the test was, and going through that experience?

00:17:35.000 --> 00:17:50.000
Oh, yes, how well I remember. First requirement, in order to even apply, you had to have a registered voter to identify prove that you were who you said you were.

00:17:50.000 --> 00:18:01.000
Now, if only whites are registered, what white person is going to vouch for you? There were few who would do that.

00:18:01.000 --> 00:18:15.000
The other requirement was, you had to have identification, driver's license, or social security card.

00:18:15.000 --> 00:18:30.000
And now you got to pass a test, what's the test? Interpret the Constitution, US Constitution, to the satisfactory of the voter register.

00:18:30.000 --> 00:18:34.000
And Harvard Law, you couldn't do that.

00:18:34.000 --> 00:18:50.000
Now, if you pass that, now you got to figure your age how old I am today in years, in months, and days.

00:18:50.000 --> 00:18:56.000
And if you pass that test, they may give you a card.

00:18:56.000 --> 00:19:04.000
That was true for Louisiana. In Texas, of course, you had to pay poll tax and all that kind of thing.

00:19:04.000 --> 00:19:08.000
But it was just... No, it only takes a second.

00:19:08.000 --> 00:19:13.000
So it was an incredibly difficult barrier to pass.

00:19:13.000 --> 00:19:16.000
Incredibly difficult. Incredibly difficult.

00:19:16.000 --> 00:19:25.000
And that was a part of my responsibility when I joined Martin Luther King's staff was to get...

00:19:25.000 --> 00:19:41.000
to teach voter education, teach people how to pass the test, and to compute their age in terms of years, days, months, to the day that they were applying to get registered.

00:19:41.000 --> 00:19:59.000
Now, speaking of Dr. King, of course, could you tell us the story of how you felt drawn to fight for civil rights, and how you met Dr. King and her organization, and began working with the Southern Christian Leadership Conference?

00:19:59.000 --> 00:20:14.000
Though my daddy could not read it right, my daddy, as I think about it, was gifted in that he knew how to work the system.

00:20:14.000 --> 00:20:33.000
Coming up in his era, he knew he had to pay homage to the white man. He'd call him Captain" and "Boss", and what have you.

00:20:33.000 --> 00:20:44.000
But he knew how to get what he needed to survive. He said this to me one day. He said,

00:20:44.000 --> 00:20:51.000
you can call a white man a dog if you know how and get by with it.

00:20:51.000 --> 00:21:03.000
My daddy always did his teaching by demonstration. The boss bought a new car, and my daddy walked by the car and said,

00:21:03.000 --> 00:21:18.000
this is a beautiful car. You know you are a big dog. Call him a dog. He liked it when he knew how to call him a dog.

00:21:18.000 --> 00:21:33.000
I saw my daddy using techniques to get what he needed to get, but never diminished him his manhood. He never did that.

00:21:33.000 --> 00:21:48.000
So my daddy taught me how to be a man and a proud man, even in the midst of segregation and on the plantation.

00:21:48.000 --> 00:22:00.000
So I knew what I saw happening in America, particularly where I lived. Something was wrong with that.

00:22:00.000 --> 00:22:11.000
And there became a burning inside of me and a yearning to see what I could do to change this.

00:22:11.000 --> 00:22:24.000
I had a wonderful experience about life-grade. This is not on the plantation. This is in the little town of Dixie.

00:22:24.000 --> 00:22:44.000
There were two stores in Dixie and a railroad station. I went to the summer of 52, maybe 51-52, to one of the store owners and said to him,

00:22:44.000 --> 00:23:00.000
he would like to have a summer job. His name was H.L. Whitlow. He said to me, well boy I just hired two students, they were both college students, one white, one black,

00:23:00.000 --> 00:23:09.000
and my brother-in-law is working for me this summer, and I don't need anybody. I wish you would come sooner.

00:23:09.000 --> 00:23:20.000
Well as I was leaving the store, his wife said, hey boy come here, I'm going to talk to my husband about hiring you. I like you.

00:23:20.000 --> 00:23:33.000
Well he said to me, well I really don't need you, but because my wife likes you, be here Monday morning and I'll try you out.

00:23:33.000 --> 00:23:48.000
I was working on the plantation in the field and we would go chop cotton, pick cotton, we'd go to field at seven o'clock, get off at five, five days a week.

00:23:48.000 --> 00:24:07.000
Well when I got to summer job at the H.L. Whitlow store, I had to be there for five, thirty in the morning because the field hands would stop in his store on their way to the field to get that by their lunch.

00:24:07.000 --> 00:24:23.000
So I needed to be there during the rush hour. H.L. Whitlow was far ahead of his time as a white man. He practiced in the fifties equal employment opportunities.

00:24:23.000 --> 00:24:42.000
He had a white student from Louisiana Tech working for him that summer and a black student from Grambling. However the white student worked in the store, but the black student was made in the house.

00:24:42.000 --> 00:24:56.000
Well make a long story short. He told me, I'm going to try you out and if you don't ask me what I'm going to pay you, I'll pay you whatever you're worth.

00:24:56.000 --> 00:25:06.000
Well at the end of the week he applauded me. He said, you could work. I like you and I want to keep you on.

00:25:06.000 --> 00:25:18.000
Now on the plantation, five days a week, few hours per day less, I would make $15 a week.

00:25:18.000 --> 00:25:33.000
Now I'm working six days at the store, started at five, thirty in the morning, get off at seven at night. And he said, I'm going to start you off with $15.

00:25:33.000 --> 00:25:45.000
I said to him, I could work one day less and a few hours less and made $15.

00:25:45.000 --> 00:25:58.000
And you did say you're going to pay me what I was worth. You said you liked my work. But if that's all you think I'm worth, I'm going to donate this week's work to you and give it to him.

00:25:58.000 --> 00:26:10.000
He gave it back and he said to me, well what in the hell you think you're worth. That's what sir, you couldn't pay me what I'm worth but I wouldn't work for penny less than $25 a week.

00:26:10.000 --> 00:26:22.000
And he counted out ten more dollars and my mom would say, chunked it at me, threw it at me. Well it was what I asked what I didn't write him throwing at me. I just got what I wanted.

00:26:22.000 --> 00:26:34.000
Well the first thing that thing is for me was he took sick at the end of the summer. Now his college students are going back to school.

00:26:34.000 --> 00:26:45.000
He sends his wife to my daddy's house and say, the school bus that Harry would catch at his house comes by the store.

00:26:45.000 --> 00:26:57.000
Let Harry drive before he goes to school, your car and work and our full school and work after school and we'll make it worthwhile.

00:26:57.000 --> 00:27:08.000
Well I'm part time in school and he pays me $25 a week. Now make some of, he can't pay me $25 a week.

00:27:08.000 --> 00:27:24.000
And the next summer I was paid $40. When I finished high school I was making $300 a month and no black citizen in the rural was making that kind of money.

00:27:24.000 --> 00:27:47.000
And my dad was a two most influential man in my life. He was called by his white friends a nigga lover because he believed in treating people fairly.

00:27:47.000 --> 00:27:53.000
He made such an impression on my life that I still talk about him.

00:27:53.000 --> 00:28:06.000
Do you think he ran a risk? Oh yes he did. He ran a risk. He did. But he was a Christian and he had money. And in America money talks.

00:28:06.000 --> 00:28:25.000
So he could get away with it. Yes. So if you see that as a crucial part in your journey about how people treat one another and the rights and how to demand the rights, what would be the next step in that journey?

00:28:25.000 --> 00:28:41.000
I remember this senior aged white farmer came to the store one day.

00:28:41.000 --> 00:28:56.000
He was the postmaster. He was the host of his house in his store. And at lunch time he closed the post office and go and eat. And I was out sweeping the stoop of the store and this white gas saw me.

00:28:56.000 --> 00:29:05.000
He said, hey boy. Is the post office open? He was asking me where the Whitlow had gone to lunch.

00:29:05.000 --> 00:29:19.000
And I thought about how to think fast and quickly. Now I am a boy by age. But I'm not the kind of boy he's calling me.

00:29:19.000 --> 00:29:33.000
And thirdly I'm not his boy. There's no law on the book that requires me to respond to him. Now if Whitlow called me a boy, he signs a check. He has a pay to call me boy. I'll answer to his boy.

00:29:33.000 --> 00:29:50.000
And I didn't say anything. So he came over to me and touched me on my shoulder and said, hey boy. Is the post office open? I didn't say anything. He went in the store. Whitlow was there. He said, Whitlow, well you find that they're deaf and dumb nigga.

00:29:50.000 --> 00:30:08.000
I laughed about that. He was so dumb. He didn't know that I wasn't deaf. I guess what I'm trying to say, I resisted to system in my way and got back with it.

00:30:08.000 --> 00:30:14.000
And that was my early beginnings to kind of fight the system.

00:30:14.000 --> 00:30:22.000
And as you say, your father was the model for that. He lost. He was the model. You asked me another question. I forgot to ask.

00:30:22.000 --> 00:30:25.000
So what would be the next step then I guess in your journey?

00:30:25.000 --> 00:30:45.000
The next step was I was very attentive to what was happening in Montgomery, Alabama. As a matter of fact, it may be 1950, 455 in Baton Rouge, Louisiana.

00:30:45.000 --> 00:30:56.000
The Rev. T.J. Jemison had already staged a successful bus boycott.

00:30:56.000 --> 00:31:09.000
One king knew about that and came to Baton Rouge to model the Montgomery boycott by what had happened in Baton Rouge.

00:31:09.000 --> 00:31:26.000
Well, I watched and I read Martin Luther King Jr's book, Stride Toward Freedom and was impressed with him. It just so happened, I went to a small black church college in Marshall, Texas, Bishop College.

00:31:26.000 --> 00:31:30.000
And Martin Luther King Jr was my commencement speaker.

00:31:31.000 --> 00:31:44.000
The local civil rights leader here that I call, we call the father of the civil rights movement. Dr. C.O. Simkins was on Martin Luther King Jr's board of directors.

00:31:44.000 --> 00:31:55.000
And he asked Martin to interview me when I graduated and hired me to work in Louisiana, Southern, Southern most area.

00:31:55.000 --> 00:32:09.000
And in February of 1960, Martin invited me, Dr. King invited me to Atlanta to interview me and hired me on his staff. That was my first connection with him.

00:32:09.000 --> 00:32:11.000
So that was February of 1960?

00:32:11.000 --> 00:32:20.000
February of 1960, I started to work here in three board, March 1st. I was arrested first time, March 1st.

00:32:20.000 --> 00:32:22.000
First day?

00:32:22.000 --> 00:32:37.000
First day. It's interesting. I had taken a member downtown, they had a medical arts building where doctors, offices were. And I was sitting in my car waiting on them to come.

00:32:38.000 --> 00:32:45.000
And a policeman on a motorcycle that came up and said, boy, you know what a jail house is?

00:32:45.000 --> 00:32:48.000
And also I never been a jail, why would I know?

00:32:48.000 --> 00:32:55.000
He summoned three to other policemen. They escorted me to the jail.

00:32:55.000 --> 00:32:59.000
Ask, well, where's the chief? He's gone lunch.

00:33:00.000 --> 00:33:10.000
What should we do with him? Take him up. And I guess they called it book and they handcuffed me. I mean, fingerprinted me and took my mother and all that.

00:33:10.000 --> 00:33:13.000
And finally, the chief came.

00:33:13.000 --> 00:33:21.000
They put me on the elevator with the chief and the chief took me to his office and said, you have a bright future in three board.

00:33:22.000 --> 00:33:28.000
You just graduated from Bishop College and you're young. You got a role-church up there.

00:33:28.000 --> 00:33:37.000
And I want to advise you not to ruin your future by fooling with the damn communist Martin Luther King Jr.

00:33:37.000 --> 00:33:45.000
And he gave me this advice. And finally, he said, what are you going to do?

00:33:46.000 --> 00:33:51.000
As soon as you release me, I'm going to go to work.

00:33:51.000 --> 00:33:56.000
And I said, okay, lock him up. So what's here we're charging with?

00:33:56.000 --> 00:34:08.000
Oh hell, charging with careless and reckless. So my first offense was careless and reckless driving and neither police officer had seen me drive.

00:34:09.000 --> 00:34:11.000
And you were sitting in a park vehicle?

00:34:11.000 --> 00:34:17.000
Yeah, in a park vehicle. And had been sitting there for 30 or more minutes before he came along.

00:34:17.000 --> 00:34:24.000
I was arrested. I don't know how many times. I didn't see that as something to be clever or something.

00:34:24.000 --> 00:34:31.000
I was one of four children. My dad had never went to jail and none of my siblings went to jail.

00:34:32.000 --> 00:34:36.000
I am breaking that record. So I didn't keep up with it.

00:34:36.000 --> 00:34:45.000
The most, the other most memorable arrest was the last time Dr. King was in Shreveport.

00:34:45.000 --> 00:34:55.000
He is executive director Dr. Wyatt Tee Walker and I. He had this service where King was preaching.

00:34:56.000 --> 00:35:04.000
The Ku Klux Klan protested the service so they were marching in front of the church.

00:35:04.000 --> 00:35:14.000
And we went out and the young NAACP youth group were counter-protesting the Ku Klux Klan.

00:35:14.000 --> 00:35:22.000
So Dr. Walker and I went out to see what was happening and the chief told us, go back into the church.

00:35:23.000 --> 00:35:31.000
And Dr. Walker said, America is free. We can stand wherever we choose to stand.

00:35:31.000 --> 00:35:39.000
And of course, I'm southern born, southern parade. Don't know that I would have said that.

00:35:39.000 --> 00:35:44.000
And I made it a temple go back. He says, stay here harry-blank with me.

00:35:44.000 --> 00:35:51.000
And they arrested us, put us in jail for mental observation.

00:35:52.000 --> 00:36:01.000
We stayed there, I think, 36 hours. And many years afterward Dr. Walker invited me to his church in Harlem and he introduced me.

00:36:01.000 --> 00:36:10.000
This is my friend, Harry Blake, when I was in Shreveport. We got arrested for mental observation, a charge for which he has not been cleared yet.

00:36:13.000 --> 00:36:18.000
So what do you think they, I mean, brought that? What a bizarre charge, right? So why do you think they did that?

00:36:18.000 --> 00:36:26.000
Well, they couldn't get anything else. And that way they could hold us. That was all about intimidation.

00:36:26.000 --> 00:36:39.000
That was also all about seeing if they could dig in your background and find something, or could they create stuff to get.

00:36:39.000 --> 00:36:47.000
And so the best thing they could create on me was that I was affiliated with the Communist.

00:36:47.000 --> 00:36:54.000
Martin Luther King Jr and Dr. (Dr. C.O.) Simkins, who was here in Shreveport.

00:36:54.000 --> 00:37:04.000
We were getting our orders and instructions from Moscow, because as Negroes, you were too dumb to think had to have somebody thank for you.

00:37:04.000 --> 00:37:17.000
I came on the staff, March 1st, 1960, October 12th. There was an assassination attempt on my life.

00:37:17.000 --> 00:37:31.000
I was driving from my rural church on a two-lane highway. And the car behind me, I thought, was pulling into the left lane, the park, to our pass.

00:37:32.000 --> 00:37:41.000
And I heard this noise. I thought he had thrown a rock, but they had shot in my car.

00:37:41.000 --> 00:37:54.000
And that the split second, the bullet came. I then followed to just my radio and the impact of the glass from the bullet to four holes in the coat I was wearing.

00:37:54.000 --> 00:38:17.000
I pursued the car so I could get the tag number, reported to the sheriff, reported to the sheriff, and the sheriff said some days subsequent to that, that the owner of the car said he was he was bowling" at that time, so he couldn't have shot at me. And that's all that was done.

00:38:17.000 --> 00:38:24.000
And that's how justice worked. That's how justice worked.

00:38:24.000 --> 00:38:26.000
Don't know if I'm completing it.

00:38:26.000 --> 00:38:38.000
Well, let me ask another question, because you said that Dr. Wyatt Tee Walker, what he said when he was standing out there, maybe not wasn't quite what you would have said.

00:38:38.000 --> 00:38:48.000
And I just sort of want to ask about, there's the South, and there's how Wyatt's treated blacks and the South, far from universal.

00:38:48.000 --> 00:38:56.000
So the question I want to ask is, did SEL, SEL, you sort of really knew what they were getting into in this part of Southwestern Louisiana?

00:38:56.000 --> 00:39:07.000
Yes, yes. I'm assuming they did, because Alabama was equally banned Mississippi.

00:39:07.000 --> 00:39:17.000
However, the Civil Rights Commission said in their report that Shreveport was the most difficult city in the South.

00:39:17.000 --> 00:39:30.000
We didn't have the immaterial Medgar Evers, but we had what we had to keep Negroes on the control.

00:39:31.000 --> 00:39:39.000
Because Shreveport was basically a plantation environment.

00:39:39.000 --> 00:39:46.000
So those of us on plantation were disciplined mentally. There could be obedience.

00:39:46.000 --> 00:39:55.000
So when he said to me to go back in church, I had seen what I needed to see, so I would have gone back.

00:39:56.000 --> 00:40:09.000
But Dr. Walker from a different situation resisted, so I stood with him, and we both got locked up in jail.

00:40:09.000 --> 00:40:17.000
Now, did you find support or any for support from your parents or from your church when you got involved?

00:40:18.000 --> 00:40:24.000
Well, here's what I did. I went to my parents when I decided to accept Dr. King's invitation.

00:40:24.000 --> 00:40:36.000
I went and said to my dad and mom, the job that I'm going to take may result in my death or injury.

00:40:36.000 --> 00:40:44.000
But not only that, it may result in your injury or death because I'm your child.

00:40:45.000 --> 00:40:49.000
I want to apologize for putting you in that position.

00:40:49.000 --> 00:40:54.000
But you raised me and made me the kind of person I am.

00:40:54.000 --> 00:40:59.000
And my dad said, I'd be disappointed if you did anything different.

00:40:59.000 --> 00:41:05.000
And my siblings are younger than I.

00:41:05.000 --> 00:41:11.000
They tell me now the kind of treatment that my dad had.

00:41:12.000 --> 00:41:17.000
If the police was so him in a way, he'd stop calling him dumb.

00:41:17.000 --> 00:41:21.000
You stupid ass nigga, and what have you.

00:41:21.000 --> 00:41:26.000
And my daddy never responded when he got through with him.

00:41:26.000 --> 00:41:29.000
He got back in his car and went on.

00:41:29.000 --> 00:41:37.000
So he went through great humiliation because of me that he never shared with me.

00:41:37.000 --> 00:41:42.000
And since you've ever had your dad's death.

00:41:42.000 --> 00:41:50.000
Do you ever have the chance to talk with them and celebrate at all about some gains that were made?

00:41:50.000 --> 00:41:53.000
I don't know if this answers your question.

00:41:53.000 --> 00:42:03.800
When I helped my daddy to pass the voter test, that was a celebration that he got a chance

00:42:03.800 --> 00:42:07.000
to vote in his lifetime.

00:42:07.000 --> 00:42:16.520
The one thing that haunts me that I never did, it pains me so that I struggle to restrain

00:42:16.520 --> 00:42:18.160
my tears.

00:42:18.160 --> 00:42:25.640
I never taught my daddy to write his name, and I could have done that.

00:42:25.640 --> 00:42:35.920
But he was a man of amoral self courage.

00:42:35.920 --> 00:42:40.160
And jumping ahead again, I understand that you did run into some, quite some violence

00:42:40.160 --> 00:42:41.160
yourself.

00:42:41.160 --> 00:42:46.280
It's part of the movement if you wouldn't mind talking about that.

00:42:46.280 --> 00:42:58.400
The girls who were killed in 16th Street Baptist Church bombing, President

00:42:58.400 --> 00:43:06.280
Kennedy declared the next Sunday at day of morning.

00:43:06.280 --> 00:43:15.840
The civil rights leaders suggested that we would have memorial services in our communities

00:43:15.840 --> 00:43:22.400
that Sunday, September 22nd.

00:43:22.400 --> 00:43:33.480
I went to our commission form of government then was a commission, a commission form of government.

00:43:33.480 --> 00:43:40.680
I went to the commission of public safety to get a permit to have a march from Book of

00:43:40.680 --> 00:43:47.440
Washington High School to the closest church, Little Union Baptist Church.

00:43:47.440 --> 00:43:52.000
I think I went to the commission to the Tuesday, he said, I'll get back with you.

00:43:52.000 --> 00:43:57.800
Saturday noon, he summoned me to his office and said, permit tonight.

00:43:57.800 --> 00:44:04.520
Well, the next day, the service was going to be held in the morning and asked me, well,

00:44:04.520 --> 00:44:06.040
what are you going to do?

00:44:06.760 --> 00:44:12.080
As a well commissioner, you had five or six days to make your decision and you want me

00:44:12.080 --> 00:44:14.560
to make mine in five or six minutes.

00:44:14.560 --> 00:44:18.720
You'll see Sunday, well, I'm going to do it.

00:44:18.720 --> 00:44:23.760
He said, well, let me tell you, anybody in street food participates in the march.

00:44:23.760 --> 00:44:28.360
I will arrest every person participating.

00:44:28.360 --> 00:44:31.840
Commissar you do what you have to do.

00:44:31.840 --> 00:44:35.000
I knew he meant that.

00:44:35.000 --> 00:44:45.400
I didn't want, if I can use this expression, innocent people participating in the march,

00:44:45.400 --> 00:44:49.160
getting arrested, losing their jobs.

00:44:49.160 --> 00:44:51.600
So here's what we did, no key.

00:44:51.600 --> 00:44:53.920
We got the word out.

00:44:53.920 --> 00:45:00.400
Me at the site where the march was to begin and they did, we told them, just go into the

00:45:00.400 --> 00:45:01.400
church.

00:45:01.400 --> 00:45:02.400
We can't see the march.

00:45:02.600 --> 00:45:15.480
The commissioner was prepared and there were policemen, law enforcement people all over

00:45:15.480 --> 00:45:17.560
this community.

00:45:17.560 --> 00:45:25.680
Looked like by the thousands, they were on horses with bayonets and had garbage trucks

00:45:25.680 --> 00:45:29.600
to haul the people that they were going to arrest.

00:45:30.400 --> 00:45:38.880
It looked like there were literally thousands of black folk who showed up for the march.

00:45:38.880 --> 00:45:41.560
But they didn't show up for the march.

00:45:41.560 --> 00:45:44.080
They were amazed at what was happening.

00:45:44.080 --> 00:45:51.520
So they came out of their houses on the streets looking and you may have scenes from that

00:45:51.520 --> 00:45:52.520
if you don't.

00:45:52.520 --> 00:45:57.360
We are sure them, which you said you can see it.

00:45:57.360 --> 00:46:04.920
And at the close of the service, a lawyer, Dr. Tony Stone went to the commission and said

00:46:04.920 --> 00:46:06.360
that's the commissioner.

00:46:06.360 --> 00:46:08.560
We need to get out of the church.

00:46:08.560 --> 00:46:16.560
He said, well, on the way you can get out, you come out two by two.

00:46:16.560 --> 00:46:25.880
Well at that time, the white citizen group, Kluclaz Klan, were outside marching and protesting.

00:46:27.600 --> 00:46:34.280
I went out of the vestibule to see what was going on the services over now.

00:46:34.280 --> 00:46:41.080
And I met the commissioner and two other policemen in the vestibule.

00:46:41.080 --> 00:46:46.480
And they'd manhandle me and began to beat me inside the vestibule of church, drug me

00:46:46.480 --> 00:46:51.600
on the outside and every policeman who could get close enough to get a piece of my head

00:46:51.600 --> 00:46:54.200
with his nice stick.

00:46:55.200 --> 00:47:01.880
They thought I was dead or appeared to be lifeless and they left me late and on the lawn

00:47:01.880 --> 00:47:04.600
on the sidewalk.

00:47:04.600 --> 00:47:11.240
That was September 22nd, 1963.

00:47:11.240 --> 00:47:15.680
And my wife was fearful.

00:47:15.680 --> 00:47:23.320
My family was fearful of me getting medical attention from the white doctors through

00:47:23.320 --> 00:47:27.640
me to Dallas.

00:47:27.640 --> 00:47:34.480
And the young people at the high school decided something needed to be done and they began

00:47:34.480 --> 00:47:37.160
protest movement.

00:47:37.160 --> 00:47:45.640
And that's where the police beat them, tear gas, bombed them, went to the school, manhandle,

00:47:45.640 --> 00:47:53.160
the principal hit and arrested a white teacher.

00:47:53.160 --> 00:48:00.920
And the three-poort went into the greatest movement, I guess you could say protest movement

00:48:00.920 --> 00:48:04.480
that had experienced during that week.

00:48:04.480 --> 00:48:09.400
And of course, last two weeks ago we just finished the celebration of the 50th anniversary of Sept 22, 1963 Little Union beating.

00:48:09.400 --> 00:48:12.400
Fifty years of that movement, yeah.

00:48:12.400 --> 00:48:16.480
I mean that sounds like outright war at that point.

00:48:16.480 --> 00:48:20.160
If you don't have access to the pictures, we'll let you sleep.

00:48:20.160 --> 00:48:23.280
It looked like a war zone.

00:48:23.280 --> 00:48:27.080
So how did that play out then in the coming months?

00:48:27.080 --> 00:48:28.280
What about your own recovery?

00:48:28.280 --> 00:48:29.920
I imagine that took some time.

00:48:29.920 --> 00:48:38.680
Well, President of my school that was in Marshall had moved to Dallas, Texas, Bishop College.

00:48:38.680 --> 00:48:46.880
And that president of the school put me in faculty housing until I recovered and came

00:48:46.880 --> 00:48:57.240
back to report my wife and two children at that time.

00:48:57.240 --> 00:49:08.240
So if you could just tell us about how the movement then went on starting with such a

00:49:08.240 --> 00:49:10.680
movement on the violent beginning?

00:49:10.680 --> 00:49:18.520
Well, here's the way I interpret it.

00:49:18.520 --> 00:49:24.200
Remember I'm saying it was students.

00:49:24.200 --> 00:49:33.560
Parents knew that Commissioner (George) D'Artois was a violent man.

00:49:33.560 --> 00:49:39.040
And he had full control of the report.

00:49:39.040 --> 00:49:41.240
He was the power.

00:49:41.240 --> 00:49:44.280
He waifo feared him.

00:49:44.280 --> 00:49:50.440
And black parents didn't want that children killed or hurt.

00:49:50.440 --> 00:50:01.000
So they found a way to kind of quail that within a week or two.

00:50:01.000 --> 00:50:07.400
And one way, one thing they did, they arrested students, there's a guy in this city who was

00:50:07.400 --> 00:50:10.640
a student.

00:50:10.640 --> 00:50:17.920
The commission of the society, he has to make somebody the leader as an example.

00:50:17.920 --> 00:50:19.960
Decided he was the leader.

00:50:19.960 --> 00:50:22.520
They put him in jail.

00:50:22.520 --> 00:50:33.120
And I believe he tells that he stayed in jail, either 32 or 42 days.

00:50:33.120 --> 00:50:40.760
He could not go to a school, public school in the city.

00:50:40.760 --> 00:50:43.480
I think he moved to New Orleans.

00:50:43.480 --> 00:50:51.960
But in any rate, 50th anniversary of Sept 22, 1963 Little Union beating later, they did grant him a high school diploma.

00:50:51.960 --> 00:50:55.640
But he had finished school somewhere else in college.

00:50:55.640 --> 00:50:59.120
So that's a part.

00:50:59.120 --> 00:51:04.760
As a matter of fact, 40 years subsequent to the day that I was beaten, the city did,

00:51:04.760 --> 00:51:12.480
and I'll show it to you on the wall, a public proclamation of apology for what had happened

00:51:12.480 --> 00:51:13.480
to me.

00:51:13.480 --> 00:51:19.480
Did you want to apologize?

00:51:19.480 --> 00:51:24.840
I didn't want to be inhibited with my work here.

00:51:24.840 --> 00:51:29.240
So I got called to this church in 66.

00:51:29.240 --> 00:51:39.040
I went to the commissioner and said to him, Mr. Commissioner, I'm a new pastor in Shreveport.

00:51:39.040 --> 00:51:41.720
I know what you did to me in Louis Union.

00:51:41.720 --> 00:51:43.120
He said, let me stop you.

00:51:43.120 --> 00:51:44.120
I didn't do anything.

00:51:44.120 --> 00:51:45.120
I didn't touch you.

00:51:45.120 --> 00:51:49.640
I said, we're not going to argue about that commissioner.

00:51:49.640 --> 00:51:53.600
I want you to do me a favor.

00:51:53.600 --> 00:51:55.760
I'm a new pastor.

00:51:55.760 --> 00:52:00.480
There are things I want to get done in the Allendale community.

00:52:00.480 --> 00:52:02.600
I'd like to have your support.

00:52:02.600 --> 00:52:08.000
But before you pledge your support, I want you to know anything I've done in the future,

00:52:08.000 --> 00:52:13.920
in the past, should I deem it necessary to repeat I will?

00:52:13.920 --> 00:52:21.280
He said, well, you know, Reverend Blake, I have always agreed with your methods, but

00:52:21.280 --> 00:52:23.280
I've always had respect for you.

00:52:23.280 --> 00:52:25.960
What can I do for you?

00:52:25.960 --> 00:52:29.920
And I went to the mayor and said the same thing to the mayor.

00:52:29.920 --> 00:52:35.600
And the mayor said to me, Reverend Blake, I'm a politician.

00:52:35.600 --> 00:52:37.960
Do you remember each time you were arrested?

00:52:37.960 --> 00:52:40.200
What church you went before?

00:52:40.200 --> 00:52:45.640
I said, church with my, he said that was my design.

00:52:45.640 --> 00:52:53.580
I told them and told the church what he couldn't do to you.

00:52:53.580 --> 00:52:55.080
I couldn't, I'm a politician.

00:52:55.080 --> 00:52:56.080
I couldn't come out.

00:52:56.080 --> 00:53:03.000
I know the movement was right and just, but I'm a politician.

00:53:03.000 --> 00:53:06.360
What can I do for you?

00:53:06.360 --> 00:53:13.320
I said, Mr. Mayor, anything I've done in the future, should I deem it necessary to repeat?

00:53:13.320 --> 00:53:14.640
He said, I understand that.

00:53:14.640 --> 00:53:16.960
What can I do for you?

00:53:16.960 --> 00:53:23.960
And I showed him the condition of the church, but I also showed him the condition of this

00:53:23.960 --> 00:53:24.960
community.

00:53:24.960 --> 00:53:33.160
I went to an outdoor, operative, previous toilets in this community when I came to 66.

00:53:33.160 --> 00:53:37.960
I want to build some housing for poor people.

00:53:37.960 --> 00:53:44.920
And the city owns eight acres of land that's supposed to be a park, which has never been

00:53:44.920 --> 00:53:46.920
developed.

00:53:46.920 --> 00:53:52.120
I want you to give that to my church, to build housing.

00:53:52.120 --> 00:53:55.560
He said the city can't sell property, but give me a little time.

00:53:55.560 --> 00:54:02.720
He had an autonomous past that said property shall be sold to Mount Caenam Baptist Church

00:54:02.720 --> 00:54:05.720
for $35,000.

00:54:05.720 --> 00:54:17.840
And the use of the property is limited to housing, recreation, education, or religious purposes.

00:54:17.840 --> 00:54:30.560
And we built 40 years ago a 120 unit housing for low income families and daycare center.

00:54:30.560 --> 00:54:40.400
And then some 30 years ago, we built a high rise senior citizens tower next to that building,

00:54:40.400 --> 00:54:42.680
a couple blocks away.

00:54:42.680 --> 00:54:52.280
So that's what I started working on, helping to improve the community and helping with education,

00:54:52.280 --> 00:54:55.240
which is my passion.

00:54:55.240 --> 00:54:58.840
I just did it in a different way.

00:54:58.840 --> 00:55:05.520
So if you could talk about how you see that kind of work, housing, senior citizen care,

00:55:05.520 --> 00:55:12.520
education, childcare, being part and parcel of a movement.

00:55:12.520 --> 00:55:15.040
It is a part of the movement.

00:55:15.040 --> 00:55:17.080
Because people...

00:55:17.080 --> 00:55:26.440
You see, the movement was targeted at the immoral things.

00:55:26.440 --> 00:55:35.440
It was immoral for me to pay bus fare and have to stand in the back when they're

00:55:35.440 --> 00:55:38.640
sitting in front.

00:55:38.640 --> 00:55:43.680
It was immoral for me to go...

00:55:43.680 --> 00:55:46.680
They didn't have Burger King's end, but similar places.

00:55:46.680 --> 00:55:52.040
I have to go around to the window and pick up my hamburger.

00:55:52.040 --> 00:56:02.560
It's immoral for a bus station to have a restroom and I can't go to it.

00:56:02.560 --> 00:56:07.120
I can't drink out of it because it says white only.

00:56:07.120 --> 00:56:13.840
That's one of the things the movement was focusing on.

00:56:13.840 --> 00:56:17.240
I may be the only person in America who sees it this way.

00:56:17.240 --> 00:56:19.880
I don't think Martin Luther King Jr, I know I didn't.

00:56:19.880 --> 00:56:28.600
We were concerned about the kind of integration we got, particularly in school.

00:56:28.600 --> 00:56:38.760
We weren't asking for them to integrate the schools necessary, necessarily, but give

00:56:38.760 --> 00:56:45.320
the black school the same funding and the same capable teachers that you give to the white

00:56:45.320 --> 00:56:47.840
school.

00:56:47.840 --> 00:56:57.480
But the system in America is smart.

00:56:57.480 --> 00:57:05.080
They took control and gave us a kind of integration that we weren't looking for.

00:57:05.080 --> 00:57:13.760
Brushed us from our neighborhoods to the white schools and closed black schools and still

00:57:13.760 --> 00:57:22.960
the black schools that were left still had inferior curriculum.

00:57:22.960 --> 00:57:26.480
In the sense, I may be the only person in America.

00:57:26.480 --> 00:57:30.840
In the sense, we got duped.

00:57:30.840 --> 00:57:39.360
Now once you open up the hotels and the restaurants, if I don't have a decent income, I still

00:57:39.360 --> 00:57:41.600
can't go there.

00:57:41.600 --> 00:57:55.400
That's where I began to focus myself to get stores to hire blacks in places.

00:57:55.400 --> 00:57:57.400
I like to tell this.

00:57:57.400 --> 00:58:00.720
I was a cashier in the Whitlow store in the 50s.

00:58:00.720 --> 00:58:03.280
I didn't go into Seagal Box to make change.

00:58:03.280 --> 00:58:05.720
I went into cashier and stuff.

00:58:05.720 --> 00:58:15.280
I was a cashier in the country 10, 15 years before we got a black cashier in the city.

00:58:15.280 --> 00:58:16.960
That's why I keep going back to Whitlow.

00:58:16.960 --> 00:58:26.200
He helped me do stuff that even the city's street would not do it.

00:58:26.200 --> 00:58:30.800
How are your relations now with some of these people that you went through all of this

00:58:30.800 --> 00:58:32.800
against or with?

00:58:32.800 --> 00:58:38.640
Obviously, the Whitlow guy, he was 60 years old in the 50s.

00:58:38.640 --> 00:58:41.280
He's gone to heaven.

00:58:41.280 --> 00:58:48.080
Have good relationship with white.

00:58:48.080 --> 00:58:55.480
Have good relationship.

00:58:55.480 --> 00:59:00.000
I have no interest in Seagal.

00:59:00.000 --> 00:59:03.040
I won't say I don't have an interest in politics.

00:59:03.040 --> 00:59:07.080
I have no interest in being a politician, holding position.

00:59:07.080 --> 00:59:08.600
Don't let it all.

00:59:08.600 --> 00:59:12.640
But I do want to determine who gets the position.

00:59:12.640 --> 00:59:19.720
I would never want to be a mayor because if you are mayor, you are one or two term mayor.

00:59:19.720 --> 00:59:23.520
But if you make mayor, you are mayor every time you make one.

00:59:23.520 --> 00:59:27.680
That's my position.

00:59:27.680 --> 00:59:28.680
Guess I answered your question.

00:59:28.680 --> 00:59:31.560
Yes, it does lead me to another one.

00:59:31.560 --> 00:59:38.800
Where has the source of black power and the church in the church or elsewhere?

00:59:38.800 --> 00:59:46.840
Another way of asking that is who have been your allies as you have worked on these issues?

00:59:46.840 --> 00:59:54.560
I think if you ask other citizens, you get different responses.

00:59:54.560 --> 01:00:07.560
And as I see it, the power has been in the black church and still is because every Sunday

01:00:07.560 --> 01:00:19.480
morning you get a captive audience and you can kind of mold and make in your area your

01:00:19.480 --> 01:00:26.480
church, your community, what you want to see happen in the salt, salt the diet.

01:00:26.480 --> 01:00:28.480
Yes, exactly, exactly.

01:00:28.480 --> 01:00:33.960
We will salt the diet.

01:00:33.960 --> 01:00:41.760
When Martin Luther King Jr first came to Shreveville, during those years, blacks were fearful of his

01:00:41.760 --> 01:00:42.760
presence.

01:00:42.760 --> 01:00:54.040
Because on that he died that everybody, for the most part, saw him as the prophet.

01:00:54.040 --> 01:01:02.720
There were several churches who voted that he could not preach.

01:01:02.720 --> 01:01:09.520
As a matter of fact, this church was vacant in the height of the civil rights movement during

01:01:09.520 --> 01:01:11.200
the 1961.

01:01:11.200 --> 01:01:18.760
My name came up as a candidate and they voted.

01:01:18.760 --> 01:01:25.240
Harry Blake is a good man, he's a good leader, but he made it out, church bomb got burned.

01:01:25.240 --> 01:01:31.800
And they didn't realize that was a blessing with the condition that church built.

01:01:31.800 --> 01:01:37.640
It was only after the civil rights movement had taken a different direction that they considered

01:01:37.640 --> 01:01:44.840
to call me.

01:01:44.840 --> 01:01:49.880
This has been wonderful and let's start to wrap up.

01:01:49.880 --> 01:01:52.680
So what are you focusing on now?

01:01:52.680 --> 01:01:56.880
Focusing at going home sitting there.

01:01:56.880 --> 01:02:00.640
I'll be 80 years old next year.

01:02:00.640 --> 01:02:06.760
My focus now is all over America.

01:02:06.760 --> 01:02:14.440
All over America and it cannot be denied that the school system needs help.

01:02:14.440 --> 01:02:17.440
In trouble.

01:02:17.440 --> 01:02:30.680
And unfortunately for me, I've always tackled what appeared to be impossible.

01:02:30.680 --> 01:02:41.000
When I read statistics that the system decides by the time a Blake boy becomes fourth grade

01:02:41.000 --> 01:02:51.640
depending on how he's performing, they determine how many prison cells to be by fourth grade

01:02:51.640 --> 01:02:59.680
students.

01:02:59.680 --> 01:03:05.400
Like males in America, I am trouble.

01:03:05.400 --> 01:03:19.960
So it is my, it is incumbent upon me to have a ministry in my church to develop strong,

01:03:19.960 --> 01:03:22.240
moral black men.

01:03:22.240 --> 01:03:24.520
That's where I'm going.

01:03:24.520 --> 01:03:31.080
What do you do with the fourth grade, third and fourth grade boys?

01:03:31.080 --> 01:03:36.320
Teach them how to read.

01:03:36.320 --> 01:03:41.440
Do you start a school and compete with the public school?

01:03:41.440 --> 01:03:43.520
I'm not sure that I want to do that.

01:03:43.520 --> 01:03:48.680
So three summers ago, I started a summer boy as a academy.

01:03:48.680 --> 01:03:54.000
I remember, I think we've had up to 50 in that.

01:03:54.000 --> 01:04:02.760
One boy was on second grade reading level and when we got through with him, he was on

01:04:02.760 --> 01:04:05.240
sixth grade reading level.

01:04:05.240 --> 01:04:08.160
So I know it can be done.

01:04:08.160 --> 01:04:13.880
There's a boy in this church named Walter, 12 years old.

01:04:13.880 --> 01:04:19.720
And I kept hearing that he came read, he came past fourth grade material.

01:04:19.720 --> 01:04:23.960
I said to my church, we got a had Walter".

01:04:23.960 --> 01:04:29.280
And perhaps you didn't have said this.

01:04:29.280 --> 01:04:36.400
But I said, if this was a white church, we'd find a way to help Walter.

01:04:36.400 --> 01:04:42.560
And this church, this church is so academy, they allow me to try anything that just

01:04:42.560 --> 01:04:46.200
can help people and they underwrite it.

01:04:46.200 --> 01:04:50.280
I said, out of my first church, let's homeschool it.

01:04:51.120 --> 01:04:56.040
And somebody in the background said, homeschooling in your house, not mine.

01:04:56.040 --> 01:05:02.600
So that caught on.

01:05:02.600 --> 01:05:05.360
And I did some investigation.

01:05:05.360 --> 01:05:08.360
There's virtual school.

01:05:08.360 --> 01:05:12.360
That's a term that I didn't know about.

01:05:12.360 --> 01:05:19.640
And finally, there's a young woman in this church who sympathized with my passion.

01:05:19.640 --> 01:05:24.720
I said, pastor, I've been teaching in the system, the other parish.

01:05:24.720 --> 01:05:31.440
I think she said for 33 or 35 years, I hadn't planned the retire this year, but I will retire.

01:05:31.440 --> 01:05:35.480
And that was in July.

01:05:35.480 --> 01:05:41.600
I will turn my papers in next week to come over here and help you with that school.

01:05:41.600 --> 01:05:44.600
And I'd like for you to see her before you leave.

01:05:44.600 --> 01:05:46.640
Just me and she see it.

01:05:46.640 --> 01:05:50.760
And we have five boys in that school.

01:05:50.760 --> 01:05:54.760
And we'll take some more next year.

01:05:54.760 --> 01:05:56.520
And they come every day?

01:05:56.520 --> 01:05:57.520
Every day?

01:05:57.520 --> 01:05:58.520
From eight to three.

01:05:58.520 --> 01:06:02.560
So you are homeschooling in the church?

01:06:02.560 --> 01:06:05.280
Homechooling in the church.

01:06:05.280 --> 01:06:07.280
And the church allows me to do that.

01:06:07.280 --> 01:06:10.240
That's what's so great about Mount Canaan church.

01:06:10.240 --> 01:06:15.040
They allow me to do silly, not silly, crazy stuff.

01:06:15.040 --> 01:06:17.040
And I generally make it work.

01:06:17.040 --> 01:06:20.480
We generally make it work.

01:06:20.480 --> 01:06:23.560
That's interesting.

01:06:23.560 --> 01:06:29.080
Even in the movement, which was a mass movement, it was about one-on-one change in interaction.

01:06:29.080 --> 01:06:36.080
And here's an example of intervention at a personal level.

01:06:36.080 --> 01:06:40.160
Well, anything that we didn't cover that you want to add, I'm sure there's a lot.

01:06:40.160 --> 01:06:44.440
Oh, I need more to do this.

01:06:44.440 --> 01:06:45.440
I'm so glad you did.

01:06:45.440 --> 01:06:46.440
I'm not really.

01:06:46.440 --> 01:06:48.440
You never thank my secretary.

01:06:48.440 --> 01:06:49.440
Daddy, you got to do it.

01:06:49.440 --> 01:06:50.440
For posterity.

01:06:50.440 --> 01:06:57.440
I won't be here for posterity.

01:06:57.440 --> 01:07:02.440
I really wish I could think of something else that I'd be to say.

01:07:02.440 --> 01:07:13.480
Other than Mount Canaan church is right in the center of the hood.

01:07:13.480 --> 01:07:24.840
But making a difference in the hood, and they give me full range to bring about change.

01:07:24.840 --> 01:07:31.680
Best thing happened to me was this church in the hood.

01:07:31.680 --> 01:07:33.680
John, did you have anything you wanted to ask?

01:07:33.680 --> 01:07:34.680
I want to thank you.

01:07:34.680 --> 01:07:38.880
Every question I got on the tip of my tongue is already in.

01:07:38.880 --> 01:07:39.880
Fantastic.

01:07:39.880 --> 01:07:40.880
Well, thank you so much.

01:07:40.880 --> 01:07:43.680
I can't even express how much I appreciate it.

01:07:43.680 --> 01:07:46.240
I do want you just to see this teacher.

01:07:46.240 --> 01:07:47.240
Absolutely.

01:07:47.240 --> 01:07:48.240
Absolutely.

01:07:48.240 --> 01:07:51.080
And I know some of the pictures that you were talking about, too.

01:07:51.080 --> 01:07:54.840
Yes, yes, yes, yes.

01:07:54.840 --> 01:07:59.920
This has been a presentation of the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum

01:07:59.920 --> 01:08:02.320
of African American History and Culture.

